<appendix id="security">
 <title>Enhanced security features</title>

 <abstract>
   <para>
     In this chapter, we introduce enhanced security features
     built in PostgreSQL version 8.4.x or later.
   </para>

   <para>
     SE-PostgreSQL (Security Enhanced PostgreSQL) is an enhanced
     security feature. It provides fine-grained mandatory access
     controls including row-/column- level, and security policy
     integration with operating system (SELinux).
   </para>
 </abstract>

 <sect1 id="security-sepgsql-setup">
   <title>SE-PostgreSQL setup</title>
   <abstract>
     <para>
       In this chapter, we introduce the way to build and setup
       SE-PostgreSQL.
     </para>
   </abstract>

   <sect2 id="security-sepgsql-setup-build">
     <title>build and installation</title>
     <para>
       To activate SE-PostgreSQL feature, you can specify --enable-selinux
       option in the configure script, as follows:
       <screen>
	 <prompt>$ </prompt><userinput>./configure --enable-selinux</userinput>
       </screen>
       It requires the libselinux library and header files to build.
       Please confirm its version is 2.0.43 or later.
     </para>

     <para>
       SE-PostgreSQL requires its security policy module to work correctly.
       contrib/sepgsql_policy contains the source of security policy.
       <screen>
	 <prompt>$ </prompt><userinput>gmake -C contrib/sepgsql_policy</userinput>
       </screen>
       If you can make it correctly, the security policy module is generated
       at contrib/sepgsql_policy/sepostgresql.pp.
       It can be linked with semodule command, as follows:
       <screen>
	 <prompt># </prompt><userinput>semodule -i contrib/sepgsql_policy</userinput>
       </screen>
     </para>

     <para>
       SELinux requires security context of files are associated correctly.
       Just before you invoke initdb, run /sbin/restorecon to attach
       correct security context for installed files.
       <screen>
	 <prompt># </prompt><userinput>/sbin/restorecon -R /usr/local/pgsql</userinput>
       </screen>
     </para>

   </sect2>

